        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Apo Island sits a short boat ride off Dauin in Negros Oriental, and it is still one of the cleanest community-run marine sanctuaries in the country. The pawikan show up nearly every morning along the shallow seagrass beds, and the snorkel from the beach is honestly one of the best free swims you will get in the Philippines. The trick is the boat schedule, the fees, and the wind.</p>
<p>This is a calm day trip from Dauin or Dumaguete, not the busy island-hop most beginners assume it is. Tara, here is the kwento for first-timers.</p>
<h2>Getting to Apo Island</h2>
<p>The standard route is to base in Dumaguete or Dauin, then ride south to Malatapay where the public bancas leave for Apo. Tricycle or jeepney drops you at the Malatapay market, and the boat operators register you at the small tourism office on the beach. The crossing takes around 30 to 40 minutes depending on the sea state.</p>
<h3>Boat Options</h3>
<p>There are two ways across. The public boats run on a fixed schedule and split the fare between the passengers, which is the sulit option if you do not mind waiting for the boat to fill up. The private bancas leave on your schedule and cost more, but they wait at the island for the return ride. Most dive shops in Dauin also run their own boats and bundle the trip with snorkel gear and lunch.</p>
<h2>The Fees Are Real</h2>
<p>Apo Island is a protected sanctuary and the marine fee structure is non-negotiable. Snorkelers pay one rate, divers pay a higher rate, and the fee is collected at the beach on arrival. The community uses the money for the reef rangers, the moorings, and the village school. Bring small bills.</p>
<h3>What You Will See</h3>
<ul>
<li>Green sea turtles grazing on the seagrass off the village beach</li>
<li>Hard coral gardens along the wall on the marine sanctuary side</li>
<li>Schools of jacks and parrotfish in the deeper drop</li>
<li>Occasional sea snakes, harmless if you give them space</li>
<li>The community lighthouse if you climb the short trail</li>
</ul>
<h2>How the Day Goes</h2>
<p>Leave Dauin by 7 a.m. so you reach Malatapay before the morning boats fill. Cross to Apo by 9 a.m. and walk to the village beach for the first snorkel. The turtles are most active in the morning before the day-tour bancas arrive. Take a break at the small carinderias for grilled fish and rice, then snorkel the marine sanctuary side after lunch when the visibility is best.</p>
<h3>What to Bring</h3>
<p>Bring your own mask and snorkel if you have one because the rental sets at the boat are basic. Aqua shoes help on the rocky beach landing. A reef-safe sunscreen is required by the rangers, the spray cans are confiscated at the entrance. Bring a refillable water bottle and a dry bag for the boat ride.</p>
<h2>Where to Base</h2>
<p>Dauin is the calmer base. The town is a strip of small dive resorts along a black sand beach, and the food scene is honest and affordable. Dumaguete is the louder option with more restaurants, a boulevard for sunset, and easier transport to the airport. Both work for the Apo Island day, and you can compare guesthouses and small resorts on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729757-Dumaguete_City_Negros_Oriental_Negros_Island_Region-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>Getting to Dumaguete</h2>
<p>Direct flights from Manila and Cebu land at Sibulan Airport. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines run the route daily. The other way in is the ferry from Cebu City to Sibulan via Liloan and Sibulan port, which is a longer ride but works if you are island-hopping the Visayas.</p>
<h2>One Honest Note</h2>
<p>Apo Island gets cancelled when the wind picks up. The crossing is exposed and the boatmen will not risk the trip if the swell is high. Build a buffer day into your Dauin plan so you can shift the Apo day if the morning is bad. Most travelers who miss it are the ones who only had one window.</p>
<p>Apo is the rare snorkel day that lives up to the promise. Slow morning, turtles within fin range, lunch at a carinderia, and back to Dauin for sunset.</p>
