        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Olango Island sits a short banca ride east of Mactan and most Cebu travelers fly over it without noticing. It is the larger inhabited island you can see from the Mactan resorts, and it holds one of the most important migratory bird sanctuaries in the country. The shorebirds stop here on their long flight south from Siberia and China, and the protected wetland is the easiest birding day you can plan from a Cebu base.</p>
<p>This is not the island for boat tours and shell anklets. This is the slow day. Tara, here is the read.</p>
<h2>Getting to Olango</h2>
<p>The standard route is from Mactan to Olango via the Hilton Port pier, which is the small fishing pier on the eastern side of Mactan past Punta Engano. A tricycle from any of the Mactan resorts drops you at the pier in around 20 minutes. The banca crossing takes around 20 to 30 minutes and lands at Sta. Rosa pier on Olango.</p>
<h3>From Sta. Rosa Pier</h3>
<p>From the pier, a tricycle or habal-habal takes you to the Olango Island Wildlife Sanctuary at the southern end of the island. The road is mostly rough concrete and the ride takes around 20 minutes. Agree on the fare with the driver before you climb on, and ask the driver to wait if you want a guaranteed ride back to the pier.</p>
<h2>The Bird Sanctuary</h2>
<p>The Olango Island Wildlife Sanctuary protects around 920 hectares of wetland, mangroves, and intertidal flats. From September to November and again from February to May, the migratory shorebirds pass through in large numbers. The resident waders are around year-round.</p>
<h3>What You Will See</h3>
<ul>
<li>Egrets, herons, and stilts in the mangrove channels</li>
<li>Sandpipers and plovers on the intertidal flats at low tide</li>
<li>Occasional Chinese egrets, the rare species the sanctuary is known for</li>
<li>The viewing deck where the rangers set up a spotting scope</li>
<li>The mangrove boardwalk for the walk to the viewing area</li>
</ul>
<h3>What to Bring</h3>
<p>Bring binoculars if you have them, the resident pair at the ranger station is heavily used and the spotting scope queue can be long. A wide-brim hat helps because there is no shade on the intertidal flats. Insect repellent for the mangroves. A long-sleeved shirt for the same reason.</p>
<h2>The Caw-oy Sandbar</h2>
<p>After the sanctuary, the standard add-on is a short banca to the Caw-oy sandbar off the northern side of the island. The sandbar appears at low tide and the snorkel along the edge is calm and shallow. Bring your own mask if you have one. Lunch on the sandbar is grilled fish from the small cantina at the boat ramp.</p>
<h2>How the Day Goes</h2>
<p>Leave Mactan by 7 a.m. so you reach the sanctuary by 9 a.m. when the birds are most active in the cool air. Spend two hours at the boardwalk and the viewing deck. Banca to the Caw-oy sandbar for lunch and a slow snorkel. Return to Sta. Rosa pier by 4 p.m. for the afternoon banca back to Mactan.</p>
<h2>Where to Base</h2>
<p>Most travelers base in Mactan because the airport is right there and the resort options are wide. Cebu City works too if you want city food and easier transport for other days. You can compare options across both areas on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g294264-Cebu_Island_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>One Practical Note</h2>
<p>The Olango banca crossing gets choppy when the afternoon wind picks up. If you are prone to motion sickness, plan the return ride before 3 p.m. when the sea is still calm. The morning crossings are always smoother.</p>
<p>Olango is the quiet Mactan day most travelers never plan. Birds, mangroves, a sandbar, and a tricycle ride home in time for dinner.</p>
