<p>Camotes is the cluster of small islands east of Cebu that most Visayas travelers skip in favor of Bohol or Bantayan. The group is made up of Pacijan, Poro, and Ponson, connected by a short bridge between the two larger islands. The vibe is honestly slow, the beaches are clean, and the lake in the middle of Pacijan is the kind of swim you only get on islands that have not been over-developed.</p>
<p>This is the calm DIY weekend plan from Cebu. Tara, here is the route.</p>
<h2>Getting to Camotes</h2>
<p>The standard route is a ferry from Danao port north of Cebu City to Consuelo port on Pacijan. The Jomalia and Super Shuttle Ferry operators run the crossing on a fixed schedule, with the first boat in the morning and the last boat around mid-afternoon. The ride takes around two hours and is comfortable enough on a calm day.</p>
<h3>From Cebu City to Danao</h3>
<p>A bus from the Cebu North Bus Terminal to Danao takes around one and a half hours. Grab or a private van is faster if you are starting from Mactan. The Danao port is small and the ferry queue is straightforward, but arrive at least 30 minutes before the scheduled departure during weekends and holidays.</p>
<h2>The Three Islands</h2>
<p>Pacijan is the western island and holds Consuelo port, the main beach area at Santiago Bay, and Lake Danao in the interior. Poro is the eastern island, connected by a short causeway bridge, and holds the Mangodlong rock formations and the town of Poro. Ponson is the smaller northern island and is mostly fishing villages, rarely visited by day-trippers.</p>
<h3>Santiago Bay</h3>
<p>Santiago Bay on the western coast of Pacijan is the standard base. The long white sand beach faces west and the sunset is the consistent highlight. Small resorts and guesthouses line the beach road. The water is shallow for a long way out, which makes it safe for swimmers of all levels.</p>
<h3>Lake Danao</h3>
<p>Lake Danao is the freshwater lake in the middle of Pacijan, about 20 minutes by motorbike from Santiago Bay. The lake has small bancas for hire, a couple of carinderias on the shore, and a few overgrown trails. The water is calm and the swim is refreshing after the hot ride in.</p>
<h3>Mangodlong</h3>
<p>Mangodlong on Poro Island is the dramatic rock formation scene with the offshore stack rising out of the water. The viewpoint resort has a paid entrance for non-guests and the cliff jump is popular with weekend groups. Worth a half-day from your Santiago Bay base.</p>
<h2>How to Get Around</h2>
<p>The standard transport on Camotes is a motorbike rental from any of the guesthouses or a habal-habal hired by the day. The bike route between Pacijan and Poro is a flat 30-minute ride across the causeway. Tricycles work for short hops but are slower for the cross-island trips.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Cash, the ATMs on Camotes are unreliable</li>
<li>A power bank, brownouts happen on the smaller islands</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a hat</li>
<li>A light long-sleeve for the motorbike rides</li>
<li>A book or downloaded movie, the Wi-Fi is slow</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The bulk of the accommodation is along Santiago Bay on Pacijan. Options range from cheap guesthouses to small beachfront resorts. There are no large chain hotels. For comparing the smaller properties, you can check listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g668040-Camotes_Islands_Cebu_Province_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>Getting Out</h2>
<p>The afternoon ferries back to Danao leave around 1 p.m. and 4 p.m. Build a buffer if you are flying out the same day because the ferry can run late when the sea picks up. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> has the most slots out of Mactan.</p>
<p>Camotes is the kind of weekend that resets the pace. Lake swim, sunset at Santiago Bay, grilled fish for dinner, and a Sunday morning that does not require an alarm.</p>
