        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Calaguas is the cluster of small islands off the northern coast of Camarines Norte, and Tinaga Island holds the long white-sand beach most travelers come for. The beach is around two kilometers of fine powdery sand facing an open bay with no permanent buildings, only seasonal camping setups and a few small resorts on the back side of the cove. The route in is rough, the wind can cancel the boat, and the rewards are honest.</p>
<p>This is the DIY camping weekend, not a packaged tour. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>Getting to Calaguas</h2>
<p>The standard route from Manila is an overnight bus to Daet, then a tricycle or jeepney to Paracale or Vinzons port, then a banca crossing to Mahabang Buhangin on Tinaga Island.</p>
<h3>Manila to Daet</h3>
<p>The overnight buses leave from the Cubao or Pasay terminals, with DLTBCo, Superlines, and Philtranco running the route. The ride takes around eight to nine hours depending on traffic. Arrive in Daet by early morning so you catch the first jeepney to the port.</p>
<h3>The Banca Crossing</h3>
<p>From Paracale port, the public banca to Tinaga runs on a fixed morning schedule and split the fare. The crossing takes around two and a half hours on a calm day, longer when the sea picks up. The cleaner option is a chartered banca from Vinzons port, which leaves on your schedule and is more comfortable if you are with a group.</p>
<h3>When the Boat Gets Cancelled</h3>
<p>The Calaguas crossing is exposed and the boatmen will not risk the trip if the wind is high. Habagat season from July to October has the most cancellations. The safest months are March to May, with February as the shoulder.</p>
<h2>What Mahabang Buhangin Looks Like</h2>
<p>The beach is a long curving stretch of fine white sand backed by coconut trees and a low ridge of grass. There is no electricity, no Wi-Fi, no shops past the small cantina at the camping area. The water is shallow for a long way out, clean enough for a full-day swim, and warm year-round.</p>
<h3>Where You Sleep</h3>
<ul>
<li>Pitched tents at the main camping area, rented from the locals</li>
<li>Your own tent if you brought one, with a small camping fee</li>
<li>Basic huts at the few small resorts on the back side of the cove</li>
<li>Hammocks under the coconut trees if you want the budget setup</li>
</ul>
<h3>What You Eat</h3>
<p>The standard arrangement is to bring your own food and ice, then pay the local cantina to grill the fish or pork you brought. Sometimes the cantina has its own catch of the day for sale. Rice and basic condiments are usually available, but bring your own snacks, water, and coffee.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Pack like a camping trip, not a beach vacation.</p>
<ul>
<li>Headlamp or strong flashlight, there is no electricity at the beach</li>
<li>Power bank, fully charged, for the two days</li>
<li>Cash in small bills, no ATMs anywhere on the island</li>
<li>Insect repellent for sunset and the early evening</li>
<li>A light tarp or rashguard for the boat ride, you will get wet</li>
<li>A dry bag for your phone and wallet</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a wide-brim hat</li>
<li>Trash bags, you carry your trash back to the mainland</li>
</ul>
<h2>How to Plan Two Nights</h2>
<p>Day one is the travel day. Arrive at Mahabang Buhangin by mid-afternoon, set up the camp, and walk the length of the beach for the sunset. Day two is the slow day. Swim in the morning, nap through the heat of the afternoon, and walk to the small hill at the south end of the beach for the wide view of the cove. Day three is the return trip, with the morning banca back to the mainland and the afternoon bus to Manila.</p>
<h2>If You Want a Roof Over Your Head</h2>
<p>The small resorts on the back side of the cove offer basic huts and shared bathrooms. If camping is not for you, this is the easier option. For listings you can cross-check on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g665148-Daet_Camarines_Norte_Province_Bicol_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>, though Calaguas itself is under-listed and most bookings happen direct with the camping operators in Daet.</p>
<p>Calaguas still does the job for travelers who are not chasing comfort. Two nights, one long beach, and a kwento that holds up after you get home.</p>
