        'excerpt' => 'The Pinatubo crater lake is still the easiest big-volcano day from Manila. Here is the 4x4 route, the trek, and what to bring.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt Pinatubo erupted in 1991 and left behind a crater lake that is now one of the most surreal day trips you can do from Manila. The standard route is a 4x4 ride across the lahar fields from Capas in Tarlac, then a short trek up to the crater rim, then the descent to the lake itself. The whole thing is doable in one long day if you leave Manila before sunrise.</p>
<p>This is not a technical climb. It is a 4x4 day with a short hike at the end. Tara, here is the practical read.</p>
<h2>Getting to the Jump-Off</h2>
<p>The standard jump-off is the Pinatubo Spa Town in Sta. Juliana, Capas, Tarlac. From Manila, the route is NLEX north, exit at Mabalacat or Concepcion, then the small roads to Capas. The full drive is around three and a half to four hours.</p>
<h3>By Bus</h3>
<p>The bus route is from Cubao or Pasay to Capas via Victory Liner. The trip takes around four hours. From the Capas terminal, a tricycle to the Sta. Juliana jump-off takes around 30 minutes. The DIY route is doable but most travelers book a private van package because the tour operators include the bus pickup, the registration, and the 4x4 transfer in one fee.</p>
<h2>The 4x4 Ride</h2>
<p>The 4x4 vehicles are converted pickups with bench seats in the back. The ride from the jump-off to the trek starting point takes around 45 minutes to one hour across the wide lahar plain, with several shallow river crossings depending on the season. The driver picks the line based on the current water level.</p>
<h3>What the Lahar Looks Like</h3>
<p>The lahar field is a flat grey expanse of volcanic mud and pumice that has slowly become a strange high-desert landscape. The cliffs on either side are layered ash. The rivers cut through the lahar at unpredictable angles. Bring sunglasses, the glare off the white surface is intense.</p>
<h2>The Trek</h2>
<p>From the trek starting point, the walk to the crater rim takes around 45 minutes to one hour at a steady pace. The trail is rocky but well-marked, with several rest stops and a couple of short ladder sections. The final climb to the rim is the hardest part of the day.</p>
<h3>The Crater Lake</h3>
<p>The crater lake itself is a deep emerald green that looks unreal in the noon light. Swimming was banned years ago because of the unstable lake bed, but you can sit at the viewing deck and walk down to the shore. The crater walls are steep and the silence at the top is the part most travelers remember.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trekking shoes or sturdy sneakers with grip</li>
<li>A light long-sleeve for the 4x4 ride, the wind is cold in the morning</li>
<li>Sunglasses for the lahar glare</li>
<li>A wide-brim hat for the trek</li>
<li>At least two liters of water</li>
<li>Snacks, the only food stop is the breakfast at the spa town</li>
<li>A waterproof bag, the river crossings can splash</li>
<li>Cash, the registration fees are paid at the jump-off</li>
</ul>
<h2>How the Day Goes</h2>
<p>Leave Manila by 3 a.m. so you arrive at Sta. Juliana by 6:30 a.m. for the briefing and breakfast. The 4x4 ride starts by 7 a.m. and reaches the trek starting point by 8 a.m. The trek up takes one hour. Sit at the crater for one to two hours, then trek down, ride the 4x4 back, and reach Sta. Juliana by 2 p.m. Lunch at the spa town, then drive back to Manila by early evening.</p>
<h2>Best Months</h2>
<p>The dry season from November to May is the safest window. The rainy season floods the lahar rivers and the tours get cancelled. The clearest light at the crater is between 9 and 11 a.m. before the afternoon cloud cover rolls in.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay if You Want a Buffer Night</h2>
<p>If you want to skip the 3 a.m. Manila drive, stay one night in Angeles or Clark and leave from there. Clark is one hour from the Sta. Juliana jump-off and has plenty of hotel options. You can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g303761-Angeles_City_Pampanga_Province_Central_Luzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Pinatubo is the rare day trip that holds up year after year. Big crater, weird lahar landscape, and home before midnight.</p>
