<p>This is the practical read for the Kidapawan trail, not a packaged plan. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Trail Permit Is Mandatory</h2>
<p>Mt Apo is inside a protected natural park and the climb is regulated by the Department of Environment and Natural Resources together with the local government of Kidapawan and the indigenous Manobo and Bagobo communities. You cannot just show up at the jump-off. The permit has to be secured in advance through the Kidapawan City tourism office, and the rangers will turn you away at the trail if you do not have the paperwork.</p>
<h3>What the Permit Covers</h3>
<p>The permit includes the conservation fee, the local government fee, the mandatory porter or guide fee for the indigenous community, and the registration at the jump-off. The current rates are posted at the Kidapawan tourism office. The guides are non-negotiable, even for experienced climbers, because the ridge sections above the assault camp are exposed.</p>
<h2>Getting to Kidapawan</h2>
<p>Direct flights from Manila land at Davao International Airport. From Davao, a van or bus to Kidapawan takes around three hours. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines run the Davao route daily. From Kidapawan city, a habal-habal takes you to the Lake Agco jump-off in around one hour.</p>
<h2>The Two-Day Profile</h2>
<p>The Kidapawan trail starts at Lake Agco at around 1,200 meters elevation. Day one climbs through dense forest, a mossy ridge, and the open grasslands before reaching the Lake Venado assault camp at around 2,400 meters. The trek takes seven to nine hours depending on the group pace and the trail condition.</p>
<h3>Day One Camp</h3>
<p>The Lake Venado camp sits in a flat grassland with the lake at the southern edge. The water is fresh and you can refill from the lake for cooking. Pitch the tent on the higher ground because the lake side gets cold and damp overnight. Temperatures drop to around 5 degrees Celsius in the dry months and lower in January.</p>
<h3>Day Two Summit</h3>
<p>The summit push starts around 3 a.m. for the sunrise. The trail climbs through a rocky boulder field and a steep scree section before reaching the summit plateau. The walk takes around two and a half to three hours from camp. The summit itself is a wide rocky area with the sulfur vents on the eastern side and the wide view of Davao on a clear morning.</p>
<h3>The Descent</h3>
<p>After the summit, you break camp at Lake Venado and descend the full trail back to Lake Agco the same day. The descent takes around six to seven hours. Knees and feet will be tired. Plan one night of rest in Kidapawan or Davao before flying out.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Four-season tent or a tent with a proper rainfly</li>
<li>Sleeping bag rated to at least 0 degrees Celsius</li>
<li>Sleeping pad, the camp ground is cold</li>
<li>Trekking shoes with proper ankle support</li>
<li>Headlamp with spare batteries for the summit push</li>
<li>Rain jacket and a warm fleece</li>
<li>Trekking poles, the descent is long</li>
<li>At least three liters of water capacity</li>
<li>Trail food, the registration breakfast is light</li>
<li>Cash for the porter and guide fees</li>
</ul>
<h2>Best Months</h2>
<p>The dry months from March to May offer the most reliable weather. The shoulder months of February and June are also workable but with higher rain chances. The wet months from July to November have unpredictable trail conditions and the climb is sometimes closed for safety.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay Before and After</h2>
<p>Most climbers stay in Davao City for the night before and the night after. The city has a wider range of hotels and easier transport back to the airport. You can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298460-Davao_City_Davao_del_Sur_Province_Mindanao-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Kidapawan has smaller guesthouses if you prefer to be closer to the jump-off.</p>
<p>Mt Apo earns the trip. Two long days, one cold camp, a sulfur summit at sunrise, and the rare feeling of having stood on top of the country.</p>
