        'slug' => 'lake-sebu-tboli-weekend-seven-falls-zipline',
        'excerpt' => 'Lake Sebu in South Cotabato sits at the heart of the Tboli homeland and runs slower than most highland trips. Here is the calm two-day plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Lake Sebu sits in the highlands of South Cotabato, around two hours west of General Santos, in the homeland of the Tboli people. The lake is one of three connected highland lakes, fringed by lotus pads and tilapia farms, with the small town spread along the western shore. The Seven Falls and the long zipline are the headline stops, but the slower draw is the Tboli weaving tradition and the highland air that drops to genuinely cool at night.</p>
<p>This is the calm two-day plan from General Santos. Tara, here is the read.</p>
<h2>Getting to Lake Sebu</h2>
<p>The standard route is to fly into General Santos, then take a van or bus to Surallah, then a van or jeepney up the highland road to Lake Sebu town. The full trip from the GenSan airport takes around two and a half to three hours.</p>
<h3>From General Santos</h3>
<p>Vans from the Bulaong terminal in General Santos run the Surallah route on a fixed schedule. From Surallah, smaller vans climb the winding mountain road to Lake Sebu. The road has been improved over the last few years and the ride is no longer the rough experience it used to be. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines run direct flights from Manila and Cebu to General Santos.</p>
<h2>The Seven Falls</h2>
<p>The Seven Falls is a chain of waterfalls along the Allah Valley, a short drive from Lake Sebu town. The first two falls are accessible by short walking trails and have the developed viewing decks. The remaining five are visible from the zipline run above the valley.</p>
<h3>The Zipline</h3>
<p>The Lake Sebu zipline is one of the longest in Asia, with two main runs over the Seven Falls valley. The view of the falls from the line is the headline experience. The harness setup is professional and the operators have a clean safety record over the years. Booking is at the zipline terminal near the falls.</p>
<h3>The Walking Path</h3>
<p>If the zipline is not your thing, the walking path to the first falls is a calm 20-minute hike through the forest. The viewing deck at the first falls is wide and shaded, and the lower pool is safe for a quick dip in the dry months.</p>
<h2>Lotus Lake</h2>
<p>The main attraction in Lake Sebu town is the lake itself, dotted with pink and white lotus pads in the dry months from January to May. The standard activity is a slow paddleboat ride across the lake at sunrise, when the mist sits on the water and the lotus blooms are at their best. Boats are arranged at the small piers in front of the lakeside resorts.</p>
<h3>What to Eat</h3>
<p>The lake is one of the country's biggest tilapia producers. Grilled tilapia, served whole with rice and a side of native vegetables, is the standard meal. The Punta Isla and Mountain Log Resort restaurants serve good versions. The carinderias along the main road serve smaller portions at honest prices.</p>
<h2>The Tboli Visit</h2>
<p>The School of Living Tradition in Lake Sebu is run by the Tboli weaver Lang Dulay's family and continues her tnalak weaving practice. Visitors can watch the dreamweavers at the loom, see the abaca fiber preparation, and buy small tnalak pieces directly from the weavers. The school is open most mornings and accepts walk-in visitors.</p>
<h3>What Tnalak Is</h3>
<ul>
<li>A handwoven abaca textile with deep ochre and red dyes</li>
<li>Patterns received in dreams by the master weaver</li>
<li>A piece can take several months to complete</li>
<li>The Tboli consider tnalak a sacred cloth, not just decoration</li>
<li>Buying direct from the school supports the weavers</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The accommodation in Lake Sebu is mostly small lakeside resorts and a few guesthouses in town. The main options sit along the western shore with views of the lake and the surrounding hills. For comparing the smaller properties, you can check listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g680066-Lake_Sebu_South_Cotabato_Province_Soccsksargen_Region_Mindanao-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>Pack a light fleece or long-sleeve, the lake sits at around 800 meters and the evenings are cool year-round. Bring cash, the ATMs in town are limited. Insect repellent for the lakeside evenings. A power bank because the brownouts still happen.</p>
<p>Lake Sebu is the rare highland trip that rewards the slow pace. Sunrise on the lake, tilapia for lunch, a visit to the dreamweavers, and a cool evening with the highland stars.</p>
