        'excerpt' => 'Bagasbas Beach in Camarines Norte runs as a friendly beginner surf spot most travelers fly over on the way to Bicol. Here is the calm weekend plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bagasbas Beach sits on the eastern coast of Camarines Norte, just outside the town of Daet, and runs a long mellow beach break that has been quietly turning out Bicol surfers for years. The waves are friendlier than Catanduanes, the lineup is rarely crowded, and the town has the slow pace most Filipino beach trips have lost. It is the kind of weekend you book when you want to learn to surf without the queue.</p>
<p>This is the calm two-day plan from Manila. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>Getting to Daet</h2>
<p>The standard route from Manila is an overnight bus to Daet. DLTBCo, Superlines, and Philtranco run the route from the Cubao and Pasay terminals, and the ride takes around eight to nine hours depending on traffic and the bus type. Arrive in Daet by early morning so you have the full day for the beach.</p>
<h3>From Daet to Bagasbas</h3>
<p>The beach is around 15 minutes from Daet town by tricycle. Most surf camps and small guesthouses can arrange a pickup from the bus terminal if you book ahead. The road is paved and the route is direct.</p>
<h2>What the Surf Is Like</h2>
<p>Bagasbas is a sandy-bottom beach break, which makes it friendly for beginners and a forgiving spot to learn. The waves run between knee-high and shoulder-high in the regular season, with bigger sets when a storm is in the area. The bottom is clean sand for most of the beach, no reef to worry about.</p>
<h3>Best Months</h3>
<p>The surf season runs from September to April, with the most consistent swell from October to February. The summer months from May to July are usually flat. The shoulder months of August and March work as windows when the conditions can flip either way.</p>
<h3>Lessons</h3>
<p>The surf camps along the beach front offer beginner lessons in groups or one-on-one. The standard package includes the board rental, the rashguard, and the one-hour lesson with an instructor. Most lessons are scheduled for the morning when the wind is offshore and the waves are cleanest. Book ahead on weekends, the camps fill up fast.</p>
<h2>How the Weekend Goes</h2>
<p>Day one is the arrival day. Drop your bags by mid-morning, walk the beach, eat at one of the small carinderias, then take an afternoon lesson. Day two is the slow day. Morning lesson, lunch at the beach, nap, then a sunset surf or a slow walk along the long sand stretch. Day three is the bus back to Manila, with the overnight ride returning you to the city by early morning.</p>
<h3>Beyond the Beach</h3>
<p>If you want to add a day, the standard add-on is the trip to Calaguas Island off the coast of Paracale. That is a separate camping trip in itself, and most travelers do not combine the two in a single weekend. The other add-on is a slow afternoon at the Bicol Saro restaurant in Daet for the regional food, including bicol express and laing.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen, the beach has no shade once the sun is overhead</li>
<li>A rashguard, even with the camp rental sets</li>
<li>A wide-brim hat for the breaks between sessions</li>
<li>Insect repellent for the evenings</li>
<li>A light long-sleeve for the bus ride</li>
<li>Cash, the ATMs in Daet town are reliable but the beach side has none</li>
<li>A power bank, the brownouts still happen</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The accommodation along Bagasbas is mostly small surf camps, guesthouses, and a few mid-range beachfront places. There are no chain hotels. The mid-range options have hot showers and reliable Wi-Fi, the camps run cheaper but with shared bathrooms. For listings you can cross-check on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g665148-Daet_Camarines_Norte_Province_Bicol_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>The food along the beach front is a mix of Filipino comfort food, surf-camp pasta, and a few coffee shops. The carinderias serve grilled fish, sinigang, pork barbecue, and a good kare-kare on the weekend. The Bicol Saro restaurant in town is the regional food stop. The pasalubong shop near the bus terminal has pili nut sweets if you want to bring something home.</p>
<p>Bagasbas is the slow surf weekend most travelers skip in favor of La Union or Siargao. The waves are honest, the queue is short, and the bus home is cheaper. Tara, sulit pa rin.</p>
