        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Ticao Manta Bowl: A Diving Trip for the Patient Visitor',
        'slug' => 'ticao-manta-bowl-diving-trip-sorsogon',
        'excerpt' => 'The Manta Bowl off Ticao Island is one of the country\'s best big-fish dives. Here is the practical Sorsogon route.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Manta Bowl is a shallow reef seamount off the southern tip of Ticao Island in Masbate, and during the right months it is one of the country's most reliable manta ray cleaning stations. The dive site sits in the strong current of the Ticao Pass, and the mantas show up at the cleaning station in numbers that few other Philippine dives can match. The trip is not a quick one, but for divers with the patience, it pays off.</p>
<p>This is the practical read on the Manta Bowl from a Sorsogon base. Tara, here is the route.</p>
<h2>Getting to Ticao</h2>
<p>The standard route is to fly into Legazpi from Manila, drive south to Pilar in Sorsogon, then take the small ferry across to San Jacinto on Ticao Island. The full trip from the Legazpi airport takes around four to five hours including the ferry.</p>
<h3>From Legazpi to Pilar</h3>
<p>A van or jeepney from the Legazpi grand terminal to Pilar takes around two hours along the Sorsogon coastal road. From Pilar, the ferry to San Jacinto runs on a fixed schedule, with the morning crossings being the most reliable. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines run the Manila to Legazpi route daily.</p>
<h3>On Ticao</h3>
<p>From San Jacinto port, a habal-habal or van takes you to the dive resorts on the western coast of Ticao, around one hour from the port. Most resorts arrange the pickup if you book ahead. The road on Ticao is rough in places and the ride is slow.</p>
<h2>What the Manta Bowl Is</h2>
<p>The Manta Bowl is a shallow plateau between Ticao and Burias islands, swept by the strong currents of the Ticao Pass. The cleaning station on the plateau attracts manta rays that come in to be cleaned by the resident wrasses and butterflyfish. The dive is shallow at around 18 to 22 meters, but the current is real and the visibility can swing wildly depending on the tide.</p>
<h3>Best Months</h3>
<p>The reliable manta season runs from December to May, with the highest sightings from February to April. The wet months from June to November have unpredictable conditions and most dive operators do not run the Manta Bowl trip during this window. Book in the dry season for the best chance.</p>
<h3>What You Need</h3>
<ul>
<li>Open Water certification at minimum, Advanced is better for the current</li>
<li>Experience in moderate to strong drift dives</li>
<li>A reef hook for the cleaning station, most operators provide one</li>
<li>A dive computer, the multi-level profile needs tracking</li>
<li>A surface marker buoy for the safety stop after the drift</li>
<li>Patience, some days the mantas do not show up at all</li>
</ul>
<h2>What Else to Dive</h2>
<p>Ticao has a small cluster of other dive sites worth a day. The San Miguel Wall is a calm wall dive with healthy hard coral. The Bat Cave is a swim-through with a colony of small bats in the upper chambers. The Halea Reef is a softer drift suitable for less experienced divers. Most operators bundle these into a two-day package with the Manta Bowl as the headline.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The accommodation on Ticao is mostly small dive resorts on the western coast. The Ticao Island Resort is the most established. There are a few smaller guesthouses in San Jacinto and Monreal. For comparing options, you can check listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3556985-Ticao_Island_Masbate_Province_Bicol_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Most divers book the room and the dives as a package directly with the resort.</p>
<h2>The Donsol Add-On</h2>
<p>The classic Bicol diving combo is Ticao plus Donsol. Donsol is on the Sorsogon mainland and runs the whale shark snorkel interactions in season. Combine the two if you are already in the area. The Donsol whale shark season runs from November to June with peak from February to May, which overlaps with the Manta Bowl window.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Pack like a dive trip in a remote area. Bring your own mask and snorkel because the rentals are basic. A dive computer, a surface marker buoy, and a reef hook are the personal kit you should not borrow. Cash in small bills, the resorts accept some cards but the smaller fees are cash only. A power bank because the brownouts on Ticao still happen.</p>
<p>The Manta Bowl is the patient diver's trip. The current is real, the show is uncertain, and the days the mantas show up are the days you remember for years.</p>
