        'title' => 'Bolinao Falls and Cape Bolinao: A Calm Pangasinan Day',
        'slug' => 'bolinao-falls-cape-bolinao-day-trip',
        'excerpt' => 'Bolinao has more than the beaches everyone visits. Here is the inland falls loop and the lighthouse at the end.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Most travelers go to Bolinao for Patar Beach and leave it at that. The town has a quieter day waiting inland, between the three Bolinao Falls in barangay Samang Norte and the Cape Bolinao Lighthouse at the north-western tip. The falls run cool and clear, the lighthouse holds the wide afternoon view, and the loop works as a calm second day after the beach.</p>
<p>This is the slow Bolinao day. Tara, here is the route.</p>
<h2>Getting Around Bolinao</h2>
<p>The standard transport for the day is a tricycle hired for the full route. The fixed-fare arrangement is straightforward, with most tricycle drivers offering the Falls plus Lighthouse loop as a single package. Negotiate the rate at the start, agree on the waiting time at each stop, and the rest of the day runs easy.</p>
<h3>If You Have Your Own Vehicle</h3>
<p>The roads to the falls and the lighthouse are mostly paved with a few rough sections. A small car can make the trip without issues. A motorcycle is faster but the inland roads have unmarked sections that get slippery in the wet months.</p>
<h2>The Three Falls</h2>
<p>The three Bolinao Falls sit close together in barangay Samang Norte, about 30 minutes by tricycle from the town center. Each has its own entrance, its own short trail from the parking area, and its own swimming pool at the base.</p>
<h3>Bolinao Falls 1</h3>
<p>The first falls is the smallest of the three and the most family-friendly. The pool is shallow at the edges and deeper at the center, with a wide flat area for picnics. The trail in is a short flat walk from the parking. This is the falls most groups start with.</p>
<h3>Bolinao Falls 2</h3>
<p>The second falls is the most dramatic. The water drops from a higher cliff into a deeper pool that allows for short cliff jumps from the side rocks. The trail in is a slightly longer descent down a stone path. The crowd is younger and the energy is louder than the first falls.</p>
<h3>Bolinao Falls 3</h3>
<p>The third falls is the quietest of the three. The pool is the smallest and the surrounding forest is denser. The trail in is short but uneven. This is the falls to choose if you want a slower swim away from the weekend crowd.</p>
<h3>What to Bring</h3>
<ul>
<li>Aqua shoes for the rocky pool bottoms</li>
<li>A dry bag for your phone and wallet</li>
<li>A change of clothes for the ride back</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen and insect repellent</li>
<li>Snacks, the carinderias at the entrance are basic</li>
<li>Cash for the multiple small fees</li>
</ul>
<h2>Cape Bolinao Lighthouse</h2>
<p>The Cape Bolinao Lighthouse sits on the highest point of the Bolinao peninsula, with the lighthouse tower rising over the cliff edge and the wide view of the West Philippine Sea. The drive from the falls area takes around 30 to 40 minutes through the coastal road past Patar Beach.</p>
<h3>What the Lighthouse Holds</h3>
<p>The original Spanish-era lighthouse was built in 1905 and the current structure has been maintained since then. The viewing deck at the base of the tower is the standard photo spot. On clear afternoons, you can see the curve of the coastline running south past Patar to Alaminos. The wind is real, so hold on to anything loose.</p>
<h3>Sunset</h3>
<p>The lighthouse faces west and the sunset is the consistent finale of the day. Plan to arrive by 5 p.m. so you have time to walk around before the light goes. The wind picks up after sunset, so pack a light long-sleeve for the ride back to town.</p>
<h2>Adding Patar Beach</h2>
<p>If you want to stretch the day, the route between the falls and the lighthouse passes Patar Beach. A 30-minute stop for a quick swim or a halo-halo at the beachfront cantinas works as a natural break between the inland morning and the lighthouse afternoon. The beach itself is best in the dry months from February to May when the sand is cleanest.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Most Bolinao accommodation is along Patar Beach, with a few smaller guesthouses in the town center. The beachfront options have direct sand access and the in-town options are closer to the carinderias and the public market. You can compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g665146-Bolinao_Pangasinan_Province_Ilocos_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>Getting to Bolinao</h2>
<p>The bus from Manila takes around six to seven hours via Five Star or Victory Liner from Cubao or Pasay. The terminal in Bolinao is in the town center. From Alaminos, the route is shorter at around one hour by jeepney or van.</p>
<p>Bolinao runs slower than its reputation. The falls, the lighthouse, and the long ride between them make the calm second day most travelers never plan.</p>
