<p>Borawan Island sits off the small coastal town of Padre Burgos in Quezon, on the long thin Bondoc Peninsula. The name borrows from the rock formations that look like a smaller version of Boracay and the white sand of Bora, and the island runs as a clean half-day boat hop from the Padre Burgos pier. The full island-hop usually combines Borawan with two other small islands in the same bay, and the trip is the calmer alternative to the bigger Quezon beach destinations further north.</p>
<p>This is the practical read from Manila. Tara, here is the route.</p>
<h2>Getting to Padre Burgos</h2>
<p>The standard route is the bus from Manila to Lucena, then the van from Lucena to Padre Burgos. The full trip takes around six to seven hours depending on traffic at SLEX and the bus schedule.</p>
<h3>Manila to Lucena</h3>
<p>The buses from Cubao, Buendia, and Alabang run the Lucena route via JAC Liner, DLTBCo, and Lucena Lines. The ride takes around four to five hours. The Lucena Grand Central Terminal is the main hub and the connecting vans to Padre Burgos leave from there.</p>
<h3>Lucena to Padre Burgos</h3>
<p>The van from Lucena to Padre Burgos takes around two and a half hours along the coastal road south through the Bondoc Peninsula. The road is paved most of the way with a few rough sections. The Padre Burgos town pier is the jump-off for the island-hop boats.</p>
<h2>The Island Hop</h2>
<p>The standard Borawan island-hop covers three small islands in the bay. Boats are arranged at the small tourism office on the Padre Burgos pier. The fee covers the boat for the day with two captains, and the per-island entrance fees are paid separately at each landing.</p>
<h3>Borawan Island</h3>
<p>Borawan is the headline stop. The island has a short stretch of cream-colored sand backed by limestone cliffs, with a few small cottages for day use. The water is shallow off the beach and the snorkel along the cliff edge has decent visibility. The cliff sections frame the photos and give the island its small-Bora reputation.</p>
<h3>Dampalitan Island</h3>
<p>Dampalitan is the second stop, with a longer beach and a row of coconut trees that provide real shade. This is the lunch island. Most boat captains coordinate with the small carinderia for grilled fish, rice, and a side of vegetables. The water is calm and the swim off the beach is the cleanest of the three.</p>
<h3>Puting Buhangin and Kwebang Lampas</h3>
<p>The third stop is Puting Buhangin with the small cave at one end called Kwebang Lampas. The cave is a short swim from the beach and opens to a small interior pool when the tide is right. The beach is short but the cave swim is the kwento of the day.</p>
<h2>How the Day Goes</h2>
<p>Leave Manila by 5 a.m. on the early bus to arrive in Padre Burgos by noon. Drop your bags at your guesthouse, then book the boat at the pier for the afternoon island-hop. The first two islands work for a swim and lunch, the third for the cave. Boats return to the pier by 5 p.m. for the sunset over the bay.</p>
<h3>If You Want to Stay Overnight</h3>
<p>An overnight gives you the morning island-hop with the calmer sea and the cleanest visibility. The small resorts in Padre Burgos town are basic but comfortable, and you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3461552-Padre_Burgos_Quezon_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. The town runs slow and the food is honest.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Aqua shoes for the rocky island landings</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a wide-brim hat</li>
<li>A dry bag for your phone and wallet</li>
<li>Cash, no card machines on the pier or the islands</li>
<li>Your own mask and snorkel for the cleaner fit</li>
<li>A change of clothes and a light long-sleeve for the ride back</li>
<li>Insect repellent for the cave swim</li>
</ul>
<h2>Best Months</h2>
<p>The dry months from December to May are the safest window for the boat trip. The wet months from June to November have unpredictable sea conditions and the boats sometimes do not run. February and March are the cleanest months for the visibility and the cliff photos.</p>
<p>Borawan is the quiet Quezon beach day most travelers skip in favor of the bigger destinations. Three islands, one cave, one slow ride back to the pier for the sunset. Sulit.</p>
