<p>Capones Island sits off the coast of Pundaquit in Zambales, just north of Anawangin Cove, and runs as a clean half-day boat hop. The island has a quiet stretch of cream-colored sand, a small reef for snorkeling, and an old Spanish-era lighthouse on the higher rocky tip. Most travelers combine the trip with Anawangin in a single boat day from the Pundaquit pier, but Capones is the better stop if you want the calmer beach and the lighthouse climb.</p>
<p>This is the practical Pundaquit boat day. Tara, here is the route.</p>
<h2>Getting to Pundaquit</h2>
<p>The standard route from Manila is the Victory Liner bus to Iba via Olongapo, then a tricycle from San Antonio town to the Pundaquit pier. The trip takes around five to six hours depending on traffic at NLEX and the bus schedule.</p>
<h3>Manila to San Antonio</h3>
<p>The Victory Liner buses to Iba leave from the Cubao and Pasay terminals throughout the day. Ask for the San Antonio drop-off, which is around four hours from Manila on the coastal highway. The Olongapo connection works if you miss the direct bus, with a transfer to a smaller Iba-bound bus at the Olongapo terminal.</p>
<h3>San Antonio to Pundaquit</h3>
<p>From the San Antonio town center, a tricycle to the Pundaquit pier takes around 15 minutes. The pier is small and the boat operators register the visitors at the tourism office on the beach. Boat fees are split between the passengers for the public boats or paid as a chartered fee for a private banca.</p>
<h2>The Capones Island Hop</h2>
<p>The standard hop covers Capones Island and the nearby Camara Island, with most travelers adding the Anawangin Cove stop for a longer day. The boats leave Pundaquit by 9 a.m. and return by 4 p.m. depending on the sea condition.</p>
<h3>The Beach Side</h3>
<p>The beach on Capones is a curving stretch of cream sand on the western side of the island, with a rocky shoreline on the eastern side. The water is clean enough for a full swim and the sand is soft underfoot. There are no permanent buildings on the island, only the seasonal cantinas during peak weekends.</p>
<h3>The Reef</h3>
<p>The reef off the southern tip of Capones is shallow and clear, with healthy hard coral and a small population of reef fish. The snorkel is calm and the visibility is good in the dry months from December to May. Bring your own mask and snorkel because the rental sets on the boat are basic.</p>
<h3>The Lighthouse</h3>
<p>The Capones Island Lighthouse sits on the higher rocky tip of the island, accessible by a short climb up a marked stone path. The climb takes around 20 to 30 minutes and the descent the same. The original Spanish-era lighthouse from 1890 has been maintained over the years, and the viewing platform at the base of the tower offers the wide view of the surrounding bay.</p>
<h2>Camara Island</h2>
<p>Camara is the smaller island next to Capones, with a short white-sand beach and a calm swim area. Most boats stop here for the photos and a quick swim before moving to Anawangin or back to Pundaquit. The stop is short but worth it for the wide bay view.</p>
<h2>Pairing with Anawangin</h2>
<p>The classic Pundaquit boat day combines Capones with Anawangin Cove on the mainland side. The standard route covers Capones in the morning, lunch at Anawangin, then a short visit to Camara on the return. The full day works as a packed schedule, with each stop getting around an hour to ninety minutes. If you want a slower pace, do Capones and Camara on one day and Anawangin on a separate day with an overnight at the cove.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Aqua shoes for the rocky island landings</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a wide-brim hat</li>
<li>Your own mask and snorkel</li>
<li>A dry bag for your phone and wallet</li>
<li>Cash, no card machines on the islands</li>
<li>A change of clothes and a quick-dry towel</li>
<li>A refillable water bottle</li>
<li>Trekking shoes if you plan to climb to the lighthouse</li>
</ul>
<h2>Best Months</h2>
<p>The dry months from December to May are the safest window. The wet months from June to November have unpredictable sea conditions and the boats sometimes do not run during typhoon weeks. February to April have the cleanest water for the snorkel and the calmest sea for the lighthouse climb.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The accommodation in Pundaquit is mostly small beachfront resorts and a few guesthouses in the village. The mid-range options have hot showers and reliable Wi-Fi, the budget options run cheaper with shared bathrooms. For the closer Subic and Olongapo hotel options if you want a more comfortable base, you can check listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g303759-Subic_Bay_Freeport_Zone_Olongapo_Zambales_Province_Central_Luzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Capones is the calm Pundaquit half-day most travelers skip in favor of the longer Anawangin overnight. Quick boat hop, easy snorkel, a lighthouse with a wide view, and home before sunset.</p>
