<p>Talicud is the smaller island across from Samal in the Davao Gulf, a short banca ride from the Samal pier or from Sta. Ana wharf in Davao City. The island runs slower than Samal, with fewer resorts, less traffic, and beaches that still feel like a fishing village first and a tourist stop second. Talicud is the day trip Davao travelers add when they want to skip the busy Samal coast and find a quieter beach.</p>
<p>This is the calm overnight plan. Tara, here is the route.</p>
<h2>Getting to Talicud</h2>
<p>The standard route is the banca from Sta. Ana wharf in Davao City to Sta. Cruz on Talicud. The crossing takes around one hour on a calm day. Boats run on a fixed morning schedule and the return trips run in the afternoon. The other route is a banca from Babak port on Samal Island to Talicud, which is shorter at around 30 minutes.</p>
<h3>From Davao City</h3>
<p>Direct flights from Manila and Cebu land at Davao International Airport. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines run the route daily. From the airport, a Grab or taxi to the Sta. Ana wharf takes around 30 minutes. The wharf is a small public pier in the city center, and the Talicud banca line is at the far end.</p>
<h2>The Beaches</h2>
<p>The main beach area on Talicud is the western coast around Babusanta Beach and the Dayang Beach barangay. The sand is fine and white, the water is calm year-round, and the swim is shallow for a long way out.</p>
<h3>Babusanta Beach</h3>
<p>Babusanta is the longer of the two main beaches, with a curving stretch of white sand and several small resorts along the front. The water is shallow and calm, making it safe for swimmers of all levels. The sunset view across to the Davao mainland is the consistent highlight.</p>
<h3>Isla Reta</h3>
<p>Isla Reta is the more developed beach on the northwestern side, with day-use facilities and a longer organized beachfront. The crowd is heavier on weekends and the snorkel along the rocky edges is decent. Most day-trippers from Davao stop here.</p>
<h3>Dayang Beach</h3>
<p>Dayang is the quieter beach on the southern coast, with a smaller stretch of sand and almost no permanent buildings. The trip out takes a longer habal-habal ride from Sta. Cruz port, but the quiet is worth it for travelers who want the calmer side of the island.</p>
<h2>How to Get Around</h2>
<p>The standard transport on Talicud is a habal-habal or a small tricycle. The roads on the island are mostly rough concrete with a few paved sections. The motorcycles are the practical option for the longer trips between Sta. Cruz port and the southern beaches.</p>
<h2>The Marine Sanctuaries</h2>
<p>Talicud has two small marine sanctuaries along the western coast, with calm reefs suitable for beginner snorkelers. The sanctuaries are managed by the local barangays and the entrance fees go back to the reef rangers and the local maintenance. Bring your own mask and snorkel for the cleaner fit.</p>
<h3>What You Will See</h3>
<ul>
<li>Hard coral gardens in the shallow flats</li>
<li>Reef fish in moderate numbers</li>
<li>Occasional sea turtles in the seagrass beds</li>
<li>Schools of small jacks in the deeper drop</li>
<li>Clear visibility on calm days, especially in the dry months</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>The food on Talicud is mostly small carinderias serving grilled fish, rice, and basic Filipino dishes. The fish is fresh because the bancas come in throughout the day. The standard meal is whole grilled tuna with rice, vinegar dip, and a side of native vegetables. There are no high-end restaurants on the island, which is part of the appeal.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The accommodation on Talicud is mostly small resorts and guesthouses along the western beaches. There are no large chain hotels. The mid-range options have hot showers and reliable solar power, the budget options run cheaper with shared bathrooms. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7193493-Samal_Island_Davao_del_Norte_Province_Mindanao-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. The Talicud listings are limited, so most bookings happen direct with the resort by phone or messaging.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Cash, the ATMs on Talicud are limited</li>
<li>A power bank, brownouts still happen</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a wide-brim hat</li>
<li>Your own mask and snorkel</li>
<li>Insect repellent for the evenings</li>
<li>A book or downloaded movie, the Wi-Fi is slow</li>
<li>A light long-sleeve for the banca ride</li>
</ul>
<h2>How the Overnight Goes</h2>
<p>Day one is the arrival day. Catch the morning banca from Sta. Ana wharf, settle at your beach resort by lunch, and spend the afternoon swimming and walking the beach. Day two is the slow day. Morning snorkel at the marine sanctuary, lunch at a carinderia, nap, then the afternoon banca back to Davao for dinner in the city.</p>
<p>Talicud is the calm Samal alternative most Davao travelers never plan. Quiet beach, fresh fish, clear reef, and a banca home for sunset across the gulf.</p>
