<p>Dahican Beach sits on the eastern coast of Mati in Davao Oriental, a long curving stretch of cream sand facing the Pacific. The beach has been the home of the Amihan sa Dahican youth program for years, with the volunteer skimboarders running surf and skim lessons and supporting the local sea turtle conservation effort. The waves are friendlier than Catanduanes, the skim setup is the best in the country, and the beach itself is the kind of quiet long stretch most Filipino destinations have lost.</p>
<p>This is the calm weekend plan from Davao City. Tara, here is the read.</p>
<h2>Getting to Mati</h2>
<p>The standard route is to fly into Davao City, then take a van or bus to Mati. The drive from the Davao airport to Mati takes around three to four hours along the coastal highway. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines run the Manila and Cebu to Davao route daily.</p>
<h3>From Davao to Mati</h3>
<p>The vans from the Ecoland terminal in Davao to Mati run throughout the day on a fixed schedule. The ride takes around three hours and lands at the Mati van terminal. From Mati town, a tricycle to Dahican Beach takes around 20 minutes. The road is paved and the route is direct.</p>
<h2>What the Beach Holds</h2>
<p>Dahican is around seven kilometers of curving cream sand backed by coconut trees and low grass. The water is shallow for a long way out and the bottom is clean sand with no coral close to the shore. The beach is exposed to the Pacific, which gives it the consistent swell and the steady offshore wind in the surf season.</p>
<h3>The Surf</h3>
<p>The surf season runs from October to March, with the most consistent swell from November to February. The waves run between waist-high and shoulder-high in the regular season, with bigger sets when a storm is in the area. The bottom is sand, which makes it a forgiving spot for beginners.</p>
<h3>The Skimboarding</h3>
<p>Dahican is the country's best skimboard beach. The shore break runs long and shallow, with smooth sand and a steady wave shape that lets skimboarders ride the back of each set. The Amihan sa Dahican program has been training local kids in skimboarding for years, and the lessons for visitors fund the program.</p>
<h3>Lessons and Rentals</h3>
<p>The surf camps along Dahican offer beginner surf and skim lessons in groups or one-on-one. The standard package includes the board rental, the rashguard, and the one-hour lesson with an instructor. Most lessons happen in the morning when the wind is offshore and the waves are cleanest. Book ahead on weekends.</p>
<h2>The Sea Turtle Conservation</h2>
<p>Dahican is one of the most important sea turtle nesting beaches in Mindanao. The Amihan sa Dahican volunteers protect the nests along the beach and run a small visitor center where you can learn about the conservation work. If you visit during the hatching season from December to April, the volunteers sometimes invite visitors to watch a release at sunset.</p>
<h3>What You Can Do</h3>
<ul>
<li>Donate to the Amihan sa Dahican program through the visitor center</li>
<li>Join a beach cleanup if one is scheduled during your visit</li>
<li>Watch the volunteers patrol the beach in the early morning</li>
<li>Buy the small Amihan merchandise from the visitor center</li>
<li>Respect the turtle nest markers and stay off the marked sections</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<p>The food along Dahican is mostly small carinderias and a few surf-camp restaurants. The standard meal is grilled fish with rice and a side of vegetables, with the fresh catch coming in from the morning bancas. In Mati town, the Badjao Seafront restaurant has a longer menu and a wide bay view.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen, the beach has no shade once the sun is overhead</li>
<li>A rashguard for the surf and skim sessions</li>
<li>A wide-brim hat for the breaks between sessions</li>
<li>Cash, the ATMs in Mati town are reliable but the beach side has none</li>
<li>A power bank, brownouts still happen on the Pacific coast</li>
<li>Insect repellent for the evenings</li>
<li>A light long-sleeve for the van ride</li>
</ul>
<h2>How the Weekend Goes</h2>
<p>Day one is the travel day. Morning flight to Davao, van to Mati, settle at your camp by mid-afternoon, walk the beach for sunset. Day two is the surf and skim day. Morning lesson, lunch at a carinderia, nap through the heat, afternoon session, then dinner at the camp. Day three is the slow morning at the beach, lunch in Mati town, and the van back to Davao for the evening flight home.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The accommodation along Dahican is mostly small surf camps, guesthouses, and a few mid-range beachfront places. The Amihan sa Dahican has a basic camp option that supports the program directly. For the closer Mati town options, you can check listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g735975-Mati_Davao_Oriental_Province_Mindanao-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Dahican is the slow surf weekend most travelers do not know about. Long beach, friendly waves, the best skim in the country, and a sea turtle program worth the donation. Tara, sulit sa Pacific.</p>
