<p>Cuyo is the small island town in the open Sulu Sea, halfway between mainland Palawan and Panay, with the long boat ride and the small airstrip that has kept it quiet for decades. The island holds one of the oldest Spanish forts in the country, a long stretch of white sand on the western coast, and a fishing village pace that runs slower than any other Palawan destination. The trip out is real, but Cuyo rewards the patient traveler.</p>
<p>This is the slow three-day plan. Tara, here is the route.</p>
<h2>Getting to Cuyo</h2>
<p>There are two ways into Cuyo and both have caveats. The faster way is the small flight from Puerto Princesa to Cuyo on the small Mid-Sea Express or AirSWIFT scheduled service, which runs a few times a week depending on the season. The slower way is the overnight ferry from Puerto Princesa or from Iloilo, with the Milagrosa Shipping Lines and other operators running the long crossing.</p>
<h3>By Flight</h3>
<p>The flights are small twin-engine aircraft with limited seats, so book at least one month ahead. The flight takes around one hour from Puerto Princesa to the Cuyo airstrip. The schedule shifts with the season and the weather can ground flights for a day or two. Build a buffer day into your plan.</p>
<h3>By Ferry</h3>
<p>The Milagrosa ferry from Puerto Princesa to Cuyo takes around 12 to 14 hours overnight. The ferry has economy bunks, air-conditioned cabins, and a small restaurant. Bring your own water, snacks, and a light blanket because the air-con cabins run cold. The Iloilo route runs less often and the crossing is shorter at around eight to ten hours.</p>
<h2>The Town and the Fort</h2>
<p>The Cuyo town is a small grid of streets around the old Spanish fort, the church, and the public plaza. The fort, built in 1680, is one of the oldest Spanish-era stone forts in the country and is still mostly intact. The walls enclose the church and the old convent, with the original entrance and the bastions still standing.</p>
<h3>What to See in Town</h3>
<ul>
<li>The Cuyo Fort and the church inside the walls</li>
<li>The old convent and the small museum on the fort grounds</li>
<li>The public market in the early morning for the fish auction</li>
<li>The small carinderias on the plaza for breakfast and lunch</li>
<li>The pasalubong shops for cashew and dried fish</li>
</ul>
<h2>Capusan Beach</h2>
<p>Capusan Beach on the western side of Cuyo town is a long stretch of white sand facing the open sea. The beach is mostly empty even on weekends, with only a few small day-use cottages and no permanent buildings. The water is shallow and clean, the sand is fine and soft underfoot, and the sunset across the open Sulu Sea is the consistent finale of the day.</p>
<h3>How to Get There</h3>
<p>From the town center, a tricycle or a habal-habal to Capusan takes around 15 minutes. The road is mostly rough concrete with a paved stretch near the beach. Most visitors arrange the tricycle to wait or come back at a fixed time.</p>
<h2>Boat Trip to the Outlying Islands</h2>
<p>Cuyo is the main island of a small cluster, and a chartered banca from the town pier can take you to the smaller islands for a day of swimming and snorkeling. The standard route covers two or three of the outlying islands, with stops for grilled lunch on the beach. The bancas are arranged at the pier or through your guesthouse.</p>
<h3>What You Will See</h3>
<p>The outlying islands have quiet beaches, calm reefs, and almost no other boats. The visibility is generally good in the dry months from December to May. The wet months from June to November have unpredictable sea conditions and the boats sometimes do not run.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Cash, the ATMs in Cuyo town are limited and unreliable</li>
<li>A power bank, brownouts still happen on the small grid</li>
<li>A flashlight or headlamp for the walk home from dinner</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a wide-brim hat</li>
<li>Your own mask and snorkel for the boat trip</li>
<li>Insect repellent for the evenings</li>
<li>A book or downloaded movie, the Wi-Fi is very slow</li>
<li>A light long-sleeve for the ferry or the airplane</li>
</ul>
<h2>How the Three Days Go</h2>
<p>Day one is the travel day. Morning flight or overnight ferry into Cuyo, settle at your guesthouse, walk the town in the late afternoon. Day two is the boat day. Charter a banca for the outlying islands, swim and snorkel, lunch on the beach, return to town for sunset. Day three is the slow day. Morning at Capusan Beach, lunch at a carinderia in town, then the flight or ferry out by mid-afternoon.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The accommodation in Cuyo is mostly small guesthouses and a few mid-range inns in the town center. There are no resorts and no large hotels. Most bookings happen direct with the guesthouse by phone or messaging. The Cuyo listings on travel platforms are sparse, but you can check the closer Palawan options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298447-Palawan_Island_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a> for context.</p>
<p>Cuyo is the slow Palawan trip most travelers never plan. Old fort, empty beach, a ferry that takes forever, and a kwento that holds up because almost no one else has it.</p>
